<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-228-264  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 228 264.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Week  Feb 12 1990 n257 p30(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>They do it with mirrors. (Bell Labs and optical computer research;includes related article 'Bell Labs has some nerve')</TITLE><AUTHOR>Leibs, Scott.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>AT andamp; T's Bell Labs displayed a prototype optical computer in lateJan 1990 that uses beams of light rather than wires to transmitand process data.andP;  The machine is crude and can barely computetwo-plus-two, but the scientists working on it say that, withrefinements, an optical computer could process all the telephonecalls in the world with a single lens.andP;  The Bell processor has noboards, chips, or other standard components.andP;  The insides holdfour arrays containing 32 S-Seeds each.andP;  S-Seeds are opticalswitches (symmetric self-electro-optic effect devices) that allowthe processor to operate at about 1 million cycles per second.andO;The federal government is investing heavily in optical reseach asone way of keeping the US ahead in computer research.andP;  Dozens ofuniversities have set up optical research centers.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   AT and T Bell Laboratories Inc. (research).andO;Ticker:    T.andO;Topic:     Optical ComputersResearch and DevelopmentPrototypeNew TechniqueFuture of ComputingExperimental Computers.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>